Pyranonaphthoquinones (PNQs) have shown a wide range of biological activities including  antibacterial, antifungal, antiparasitic and antitumor activities (Brimble et al. 1999; Sperry  et al. 2008; Naysmith et al. 2017). Among these PNQs, medermycin-type antibiotics are only  restricted to eight compounds (Takano et al. 1976; Okabe et al. 1986; Hayakawa et al. 1994),  two of which, mederrhodins A and B, were hybrid antibiotics produced by a recombinant  strain consisting of the medermycin-producing Streptomyces sp. ABSTRACT A  new  medermycin  derivative,  MDN-0171  (1),  and  two  known  structurally  related  compounds,  medermycin  (2)  and  antibiotic  G15-F (3) were isolated from the acetone extract of culture broths of  the marine-derived Streptomyces albolongus strain CA-186053. Their  structures  were  determined  using  a  combination  of  spectroscopic  techniques, including 1D and 2D NMR and electrospray-time of flight  mass spectrometry (ESI-TOF MS). Compounds 2 and 3 accounted for  the antimicrobial activity (against methicillin-resistant Staphylococcus  aureus and Escherichia coli) previously detected in the crude extract  of this actinomycete.   rodney.lacret@jic.ac.uk; Fernando reyes    fernando.reyes@medinaandalucia.es ARTICLE HISTORY received 8 November 2017  accepted 25 January 2018 KEYWORDS Medermycin;  pyranonaphthoquinone;  Streptomyces albolongus;  marine natural products;  structural elucidation

of the gene clusters encoding the biosynthesis of actinorhodin in Streptomyces coelicolor A3  (Omura et al. 1986). As part of our continuous search for new bioactive natural products from marine actin- omycetes, we detected that acetone extracts of Streptomyces albolongus CA-186053 showed  antibacterial  activity  against  methicillin-resistant  Staphylococcus  aureus  (MRSA)  and  Escherichia coli. We describe herein the bioassay-guided isolation and the structural eluci- dation of the minor component of this extract, MDN-0171 (1), a new medermycin derivative,  alongside  the  related  known  compounds  medermycin  (2)  and  antibiotic  G-15F  (3).  Additionally, we report the antimicrobial activity of compounds 2 and 3 against MRSA and  E. coli. 2.  Results and discussion 2.1.  Extraction, dereplication and bioassay-guided isolation

The culture broths of S. albolongus were extracted with acetone and the evaporation of the  organic solvent afforded an acetone extract bioactive against MRSA and  E. coli  that  was  subjected to liquid–liquid extraction with ethyl acetate to afford ethyl acetate (EtOAc) and  water extracts (H2O). These two extracts were assayed against MRSA and E. coli, the organic  extract  being  the  most  active  one.  It  was  subsequently  chromatographed  on  Sephadex  LH-20 to afford seven fractions: A–G. Fractions A and C were the most active in a test against  MRSA and E. coli. LC-DAD-HRMS allowed us to detect the presence of known valinomycin-like  antibiotics in fraction A (Pimentel-Elardo et al. 2010). This analysis also showed that fraction  C contained known bioactive PNQs, together with a minor amount of a putative medermycin  derivative whose molecular formula was not included in our in-house database of microbial  compounds (Pérez-Victoria et al. 2016). Further chromatographic separation of this bioactive  fraction allowed the isolation of three compounds (1–3) (Figure 1). The spectroscopic data  of  compounds  2  and  3  were  identical  to  those  previously  reported  for  medermycin  (Williamson et al. 2002) and antibiotic G15-F (Li et al. 1995), respectively. MDN-0171 (1) was  identified as a new medermycin analogue based on ESI-TOF and NMR analysis. 2.2.  Structural determination of MDN-0171 (1)

Compound 1 was isolated as a yellow oil. Its molecular formula was determined as C24H29NO9  +, 476.1915)  on the basis of ESI-TOF measurements (m/z 476.1922 [M + H]+, Calcd for C24H30NO9 accounting for 11 degrees of unsaturation. This molecular formula matched that of meder- rhodin B (Omura et al. 1986) but the comparison between the UV absorption patterns of  this compound (λmax at 276, 489 and 508 nm) and 1 (λmax at 239, 284 and 356 nm, Figure S8)  suggested a structural difference between both compounds. Likewise, the UV absorption  pattern of 1 suggested that this compound might be a 2,3-dihydropyranonaphthoquinone  structurally related to lactoquinomycin B (Okabe et al. 1986). The 1H NMR spectrum of 1 (Table S1 and Figure S1) displayed two exchangeable protons  at δ 7.29 (1H, s, 10a-OH) and 11.38 (1H, s, 9-OH). The most downfield signal suggested the  presence of a phenol group forming a hydrogen bond with a carbonyl function. Two mutually  coupled aromatic protons were also observed at δ 7.64 (1H, d, 7.9, H-6) and 7.95 (1H, d, 7.9,  H-7),  suggesting  the  presence  of  a  1,2,3,4-tetrasubstituted  benzene  ring.  The  13C  NMR  Figure 1. compounds isolated from the culture broths of Streptomyces albolongus ca-186053.

spectrum exhibited 24 signals: 4 methyl, 3 methylene, 8 methine and 9 non-protonated  carbons, according to an HSQC experiment (multiplicity edited). The nine non-protonated  carbons were three carbonyl groups (δ 200.5, 188.6 and 167.7), one sp2 oxygenated carbon,  attributable to a phenolic hydroxyl group (δ 156.5), three sp2 carbons (δ 115.4, 130.9 and  136.9) and two sp3 carbons bonded to oxygen (δ 75.5 and 83.3). Key correlations observed  in the HMBC experiment between the phenolic proton 9-OH (δ 11.38) and the quaternary  carbons C-8 (δ 136.9), C-9a (δ 115.4) and C-10 (δ 200.5), between the aromatic protons H-6  (δ 7.64) and H-7 (δ 7.95) and C-5 (δ 188.6) and C-5a (δ 130.9), respectively, as well as between  the exchangeable proton 10a-OH (δ 7.29) and C-4a (δ 83.3), indicated the presence of an  8-substituted-9-hydroxy-2,3-dihydronaphthalene-1,4-dione core (Okabe et al. 1986; Gilpin  et al. 1988) in the structure of 1 (medermycin derivative).

A further analysis of the NMR data of 1 revealed the presence of a 3-(N, N-dimethylamino)- 6-methyl-2-deoxypyranose unit, typically observed in medermycin congeners (Okabe et al.  1986; Hayakawa et al. 1994). Thus, the COSY experiment allowed to follow a correlation series,  starting from the pseudo-anomeric proton at δ 4.94 (H-1′) and ending with the methyl group  at δ 1.33 (H-6′). On the other hand, the large value of the coupling constants of protons H-1′,  H-3′, H-4′ and H-5′ indicated their axial orientation. The signals observed in the 1H spectrum  at 2.79 (3H, s, N-CH3a) and δ 2.68 (3H, s, N-CH3b), assigned to a N, N-dimethyl group, were  also  in  agreement  with  the  presence  of  this  angolosamine  moiety  (Okabe  et  al.  1986;  Hayakawa et al. 1994; Williamson et al. 2002). HMBC  correlations  observed between the  pseudo-anomeric proton H-1′ (δ 4.94) and C-8 (δ 136.9) and C-9 (δ 156.5) were essential to  confirm the position of the amino sugar at C-8 of the core of the naphthoquinone (Williamson  et al. 2002). These NMR data allowed us to propose the partial structure A (Figure 2). NATURAL PRODUCT RESEARCH   Figure 2. Partial structures a and B proposed from the 1d and 2d NMr data.

The partial structure B (Figure 2) could be inferred from the extensive analysis of 1D and  2D NMR experiments. Thereby, the methyl group at δ 1.32 (3H, d, 5.6, H-13) showed coupling  in the COSY spectrum with the proton at δ 4.14 (1H, q, 5.6, H-1) whose carbon signal appears  at δ 64.0 (sp3 carbon) indicating that an oxygenated function is located at this position. A  second oxygenated function was suggested based on the chemical shifts of the methine  proton at δ 4.39 (1H, m, H-3) and its carbon at δ 64.9. The signal of H-3 showed COSY cou- plings with two methylene groups at δ 2.36 and 2.19 (H-4a and H-4b), and 3.05 and 2.84  (H-11a and H-11b). The HMBC correlations of H-11 (δ 2.84 and 3.05) with the carbonyl group  at C-12 (δ 167.7) and between H-1 (δ 4.14) with C-3 (δ 64.9) corroborated the presence of  the partial structure proposed.

Sub-structures A and B were connected based on the key HMBC correlations of H-4 (δ  2.19 and 2.36) with C-4a (δ 83.3) and C-5 (δ 188.6) as well as the methyl group H-13 (δ 1.32)  with C-10a (δ 75.5) to establish a bridged bicyclic ring [3,3,1] through an ester bond between  C-4a and C-12 (Figure S10). This bicyclic system with a δ-lactone moiety in the planar struc- ture of the MDN-0171 was also found in the structure of the pyranonaphthoquinone MM  44785 (Gilpin et al. 1988). The structure of 1 has not been described previously in the liter- ature and we have given it the name MDN-0171 according to our proprietary compound  library. The relative configuration of 1 was determined based on key correlations observed  in its NOESY spectrum and its absolute configuration was suggested based on the proposed  common biogenetic origin for medermycin derivatives (Metsa-Ketela et al. 2013; He et al.  2015; Lu et al. 2015; Naysmith et al. 2017). This biosynthetic pathway led us to assume that  the absolute configuration at the chiral centers C-1 and C-3 should be the same as that found  in medermycin and antibiotic G15-F (C-1R, C-3S) (Metsa-Ketela et al. 2013; Lu et al. 2015).  The clear NOESY correlations between H-1 and H-11b at δ 2.84 and between H-3 and H-4a,  H-4b, H-11a and H-11b indicated that the ester function is at the bottom face of the ring  (Figure S11). Only a trans configuration at the C-4a/C-10a ring fusion accounts for the key  NOE observed between H-1 and H-11b. Molecular modelling clearly shows that the distance  between these two protons is 2.44 Å in the trans stereoisomer, while in the corresponding  cis stereoisomer (epimer at C-10a) equals 3.60 Å. Additionally, the model of the cis stereoi- somer displays H-4b at δ 2.19 very close (2.07 Å) to the methyl H-13 protons and another  clear NOESY correlation should be observed between them. However, such correlation is

not observed in the spectrum providing a further evidence to discard a possible cis config- uration at the C-4a/C-10a ring fusion. 2.3.  Evaluation of the antimicrobial activity Compounds 2 and 3 were evaluated for their antibacterial and antifungal properties against  methicillin-resistant S. aureus (MRSA), E. coli, Aspergillus fumigatus and Candida albicans (Table  S2). Unfortunately, the very low amount isolated of compound 1 precluded the evaluation  of its biological activity. Compounds 2 and 3 confirmed their antibacterial activity previously  reported against Gram-positive bacteria (Takano et al. 1976; Li et al. 1995; Brimble et al.  1999), inhibiting the growth with MIC values between 2 and 4 μg/mL for MRSA. On the other  hand, these compounds showed weaker activity against E. coli with a MIC range of 32–64 μg/ mL. None of the evaluated compounds displayed activity against A. fumigatus and C. albicans  when tested at a concentration of 64 μg/mL. 3.1.  General experimental procedures

Optical rotation was measured with a Jasco P-2000 polarimeter (JASCO Corporation, Tokyo,  Japan). IR spectra were measured with a JASCO FT/IR-4100 spectrometer (JASCO Corporation)  equipped with a PIKE MIRacleTM single reflection ATR accessory. NMR spectra were recorded  on a Bruker Avance III spectrometer (500 and 125 MHz for  1H and  13C NMR, respectively)  equipped  with  a  1.7 mm TCI  MicroCryoProbeTM  (Bruker  Biospin,  Fällanden,  Switzerland).  Chemical shifts were reported in ppm using the signals of the residual solvents as internal  reference (δH 2.50 and δC 39.52 for DMSO-d6). LC-UV-MS analysis was performed on an Agilent  1100 (Agilent Technologies, Santa Clara, CA, USA) single quadrupole LC-MS system as pre- viously described (Martín et al. 2014). ESI-TOF and MS/MS spectra were acquired using a  Bruker maXis QTOF (Bruker Daltonik GmbH, Bremen, Germany) mass spectrometer coupled  to an Agilent 1200 LC (Agilent Technologies, Waldbronn, Germany). Acetone used for extrac- tion was analytical grade. Solvents employed for isolation were HPLC grade. Molecular mod- els  were  generated  using  Chem3D  Pro  12.0  (CambridgeSoft,  PerkinElmer  Informatics,  Waltham, MA, USA). The structures were energy-minimised by molecular mechanics with  the MM2 force field using as gradient convergence criteria an RMS value of 0.001. The con- formational search along the C-8 to C-1′ bond was carried out using the dihedral driver tool  of the software to obtain the lowest energy rotamer along that bond. Molecular modelling  figures were generated with Discovery Studio Visualizer (formerly Accelrys Software Inc.,  now BIOVIA Corp., San Diego, CA, USA) 3.2.  Isolation, taxonomy and fermentation of the producing microorganism

The  strain,  CA-186053,  was  isolated  from  an  unidentified  sponge  collected  at  13  meters  depth close to Bata, Equatorial Guinea. A BLASTN search employing the PCR-amplified 16S  rRNA sequence (1408 bp) indicated that the strain is identical to S. albolongus NBRC 13465(T)  (100% similarity) (Kim et al. 2012). NATURAL PRODUCT RESEARCH   A 1 L fermentation of strain CA-186053 was generated as follows: a seed culture of the  strain was obtained by inoculating two 25 × 150 mm tubes containing 16 mL of ATCC-2-M  medium (soluble starch 20 g/L, glucose 10 g/L, NZ Amine Type E 5 g/L, meat extract 3 g/L,  peptone 5 g/L, yeast extract 5 g/L, sea salts 30 g/L, calcium carbonate 1 g/L, pH 7) with 0.8 mL  of a freshly thawed inoculum stock of the producing strain. The tubes were incubated in a  rotary shaker at 28 °C, 70% relative humidity and 220 rpm for about 96 h. The fresh inoculum  thus generated was mixed and employed to inoculate seven 500 mL flasks, each containing  150 mL of FRM medium (2.5% v/v) (glycerol 20 g/L, dextrin from corn 20 g/L, Bacto Soytone  3 g/L, ammonium sulphate 2 g/L, calcium carbonate 3 g/L, sea salts 30 g/L, pH adjusted to  7.4 prior to the addition of the calcium carbonate). The inoculated flasks were incubated in  a rotary shaker at 28 °C, 70% relative humidity and 220 rpm for 6 days before harvesting. 3.3.  Extraction and bioassay guided isolation

The fermentation broth (1 L) was extracted with acetone (1 L) under continuous shaking at  220 rpm for 2 h. The mycelium was separated by filtration and the supernatant (ca. 2L) was  concentrated to 1L under reduced pressure. The aqueous crude extract was extracted with  ethyl acetate to afford an ethyl acetate extract (0.233 g). After confirming bioactivity against  MRSA and E. coli, this ethyl acetate extract was chromatographed on Sephadex LH-20 using  methanol/dichloromethane (2:1) to afford seven fractions, grouped according to LC-UV-MS  chemical profiles: A–G. Fractions A (0.029 g) and C (0.014 g) were the most active against  MRSA and E. coli. Fraction  C  (0.014 g)  was  subjected  to  reversed-phase  semipreparative  HPLC  (column  Agilent Zorbax RX-C8, 9.4 × 250 mm, 7 μm; 3 mL/min, UV detection at 210 and 260 nm) with  a linear gradient of CH3CN/ H2O with 0.1% trifluoroacetic acid, from 20 to 35% CH3CN over  40 min, yielding 1 (0.2 mg, tR 17 min), 2 (1.2 mg, tR 22 min) and 3 (0.9 mg, tR 25 min).

3.4.  Antibacterial and antifungal assays Compounds 2 and 3 were tested for their ability to inhibit the growth of Gram-negative and  Gram-positive bacteria (E. coli MB2884 and methicillin-resistant S. aureus MRSA, MB5393),  fungi (A. fumigatus ATCC46645) and yeast (C. albicans MY1055) following previously described  methodologies (Monteiro et al. 2012; Martín et al. 2013; Zhang et al. 2013). Briefly, each  compound was serially diluted in DMSO with a dilution factor of 2 to provide 10 concentra- tions starting at 64 μg/mL for all the assays. The MIC was defined as the lowest concentration  MDN-0171 (1). Yellow oil; [𝛼25 of compound that inhibited ≥ 95% of the growth of a micro-organism after overnight incu- bation. The Genedata Screener software (Genedata, Inc., Basel, Switzerland) was used to  process and analyse the data and also to calculate the RZ’ factor, which predicts the robust- ness of an assay (Zhang et al. 1999). In all experiments performed in this work the RZ’ factor  obtained was between 0.87 and 0.98. MDN-0171 (1), medermycin (2) and antibiotic G15-F (3) have been identified from culture  broths of marine-derived S. albolongus CA-186053. Compounds 2 and 3 inhibited the growth  of S. aureus MRSA, with MIC values in the micromolar range. Using biosynthetic arguments  in combination with nOe, coupling constants analyses and molecular modelling, the absolute  configuration of compound 1 has been proposed. This article constitutes the first report on  the chemical composition of extracts from a marine-derived Streptomyces strain related to  S. albolongus, and has identified this strain as a new source of medermycins.
